SOME NOTIONS on a MESH of a SURFACE:
====================================

The mesh of a SURFACE is a set of TRIANGLES and/or QUADRANGLES
stored in 2 TMS a___xyzsommet  and  a___nsef, defined by:

- NBSOM vertices of coordinates (Xi,Yi,Zi) in the a___xyzsommet TMS
- the array of
(number vertex1, number vertex2, number vertex3, number vertex4)
such that number vertex4=0 if the FE is a TRIANGLE,
(1<=number vertex<=NBSOM), for the NBEFOB FE (Triangle/Quadrangle)

               *V3                         V4*
              .    .                        .     .
             .        .                    .             *V3
            .           .                 .               .
           .               .             .                 .
        V1*..................*V2      V1*..................*V2
          A straight triangle           A straight quadrangle
          (P1 interpolation)             (Q1 interpolation)

Eventually,
- NBTGS 3D tangents of components (TXi,TYi,TZi) in the 
  a___xyzsommet TMS
- the array of (number tangent1, ... number tangent8) 
(to the curved edges) at the 4 vertices of the NBEFTG TRIANGLES
and/or QUADRANGLES said CURVED FE in the a___nsef TMS
(For a triangle, number tangent7 and number tangent8 are NULL)
At each vertex of a curved FE, there are a tangent to the 2 edges
A NULL value is the tangent vector equal to the edge vector.

This storage permits a parametrization of the FE by polynamials
of degree 3 (Hermite interpolation)

             ^       ^
            /         \              ^
           /    *V3 .  \             |      V4* .
          /  .       .  \            |   .        .       ^
         / .            .\           |  .             *V3 |
        / .              .\          | .                . |
       /.                 .\         |.                  .|
      V*...................*V2      V1*..................*V2
          A curved triangle           A curved quadrangle
     (P3 piecewise interpolation)   (P3 piecewise interpolation)
      due to Clough and Tocher   due to Fraeijs de Veubeke and Sander

These FE permit C1-CONTINUOUS INTERPOLATIONS.

In fact, if a TRIANGLE is subdivided into M**2 triangles,
or if a QUADRANGLE is subdivided into MxN quadrangles
it is sufficient to store the values of M (eventually N) 
to compute the number NBSOM of vertices and use an implicit 
numbering for the 4 vertices (and 8 tangents) of the FE i.
In this case, the mesh is said STRUCTURED,
else, it is said UNSTRUCTURED.

The quality of FE DEPENDS of the QUALITY of LINE EDGES
because the boundary mesh (the line edges) IS RESPECTED in the
SURFACE mesh => A REGULAR augmentation or diminution of edge
lengths of lines is required!

Attention:
To obtain unstructured meshes as for triangulation, the
User's function TAILLE_IDEALE(x,y,z) MAY BE GIVEN!
The mesh algorithms compute the edges to satisfy the
edge length, result of the call of TAILLE_IDEALE(x,y,z).
The presence of this function is sufficient to its using.

At contrary, for STRUCTURED MESHES as STRUCTURED TRIANGLE or
STRUCTURED QUADRANGLE, the call of TAILLE_IDEALE(x,y,z) is not
done because the mesh algorithm is not compatible with!

Example for the input of Taille_Ideale:
DefVar lxf,lh2,lh3;
lh2=0.3;
lh3=0.7;
lxf=max(lh2,lh3);

DefFunc Taille_Ideale(x,y,z);
  Taille_Ideale=0.45;
  If x<lxf and y>-(lh3+lh2)*1.2
    Then Taille_Ideale=0.15;
  Else
    If x<lxf and y>-(lh3+lh2)*1.8
    Then Taille_Ideale=0.28;
    EndIf;
  EndIf;
EndFunc;
Here, upper or lower cases are not signifient.


A SURFACE MAY BE CONSTRUCTED BY THE FOLLOWING OPTIONS:
------------------------------------------------------

1 : TRANSFINITE QUADRANGLE STRUCTURED or NOT
The QUADRANGLE, eventually deformed, is defined from its
4 line edges of its contour.
Every line may be an union of lines.
A POLYNOMIAL INTERPOLATION, with respect to the vertices
of boundary edges is done.

ATTENTION:
- either, the EDGE NUMBERS of LINES 1 3 and LINES 2 4 are equal
        => STRUCTURED QUADRANGULATION;
- or, the NUMBER of EDGES of LINES 2 4 are equal (N2=N4)
      and the edges number of lines 1 3 are not same (N1 and N3)
      but N1<N3 (or N3<N1) such that N3-N1<N2
      then, the mesh contains triangles and quadrangles as
        --------L3-----------   Ni edge number of line Li
        |                   |   either N1=N3 et N2=N4   => case 1
        L4                 L2   or     N1=N3 et N4<N2 et N1>=N2-N4
        |                   |   or     N2=N4 et N3<N1 et N2>=N1-N3
        --------L1-----------                          => case 2

- or, the edge number of LINES 1 2 3 4 are different
      then , the mesh is an unstructured triangulation => case 3
      ATTENTION:
      The length of the max edge MUST BE < Sum of 3 others edges.

2 CAS POSSIBLES :
 1. The quadrangulation is the IMAGE of UNIT SQUARE
    meshed with rectangles     
 2. The quadrangulation is the IMAGE of UNIT SQUARE
    irregular meshed from the curvilinear coordinate 
    of the 4 edges by the method of COOK, GORDON, HALL     

Example: S1; I; 1; L1; L2; L3; L4; 2;
         Define an irregular quadrangulation of the
         quadrangle limited by the 4 lines L1 L2 L3 L4
         if N1=N3 and N2=N4

ATTENTION: FE may be OVERLAP because the mapping do not give
necessary a one to one point!...
Draw the resulting mesh to see if the quadrangulation IS CORRECT.
Else, try the following option 2 which correct this problem.

2 : 2D STRUCTURED ELLIPTICAL QUADRANGLE
The QUADRANGLE, eventually deformed, is defined from its
4 line edges of its contour.
Every line may be an union of lines.
The SOLUTION of a NOT LINEAR ELLIPTICAL PARTIAL DIFFERENTIAL EQUATION
SYSTEM (WINSLOW's method+corrections) maps the UNIT SQUARE onto
the QUADRANGLE with boundary the 4 INITIAL LINE EDGES
ATTENTION:
The EDGE NUMBER of LINES 1 3 must be equals AND
           --------L3-----------
           |                   |  
           L4                 L2
           |                   |
           --------L1-----------  
Example: S2; I; 2; L1; L2; L3; L4;
         Define a quadrangulation of contour the edges of lines L1 L2 L3 L4

ATTENTION: Here, if quadrangles overlap, a correction is done 
from a coefficient FADI2D for each of the 4 edges:


. After a pure Winslow method, these values are used to improve,
to control the orthogonality and lengths of the closed sub-quardrangles.

. The value fadi2d in ]0,1]  define the quotient height/length of edges
near the edges of the curved quadrangles:
. For example a value=1.  gives "squares"
.             a value=0.1 gives a sub-quadrangle ten times large than height.
.
.              d to compute = fadi2d * (d1+d2)/2

.                       d ?                     
.                       |                        
.              --*------*-----*-- 
.                   d1     d2
.
. By convention :
.   a value=0.  => NO indication on lengths of edges
.                  The angles will be improved with no other data.
.   a value=-1  => Distances are conserved during the improvement of angles.
.   a value=-2  => The distance d is the interpolation from d1 to d2
.                  on the boundary of this edge
.
.       * interpolation function from d1 to d2
.    d1 |         <--- d ? --->            *
.       |               |                  | d2
.       *---*----*------*-----*----*---*---*
.
. In all cases, the angles are improved.

Example: S2; I; 2; L1; L2; L3; L4;  5; 0.1; 1; 2; 0;
         Define a quadrangulation of contour the edges
         of lines L1 L2 L3 L4 with quadrangles 
         10 times less height than wide near L1
         squares around L2
         2 times more height than wide near L3
         and without amelioration of jength around L4
         (but with amelioration of angles to 90 degrees)
REMARK: Generally, the ELLIPTICAL QUADRANGULATION is MORE
        "ORTHOGONAL" than the TRANSFINITE QUADRANGULATION
        but its cost is greater.
        For a RECTANGLE, use the TRANSFINITE QUADRANGULATION
        which gives sub-rectangles and is cheaper.

3 : SPLINE QUADRANGLE BY INTERPOLATION of POINTS
The UNIFORM POLYNOMIAL SPLINE SURFACE is defined from
- the U edges number and its V edges number
  (In fact,U and V are the 2 parameters of the spline surface)
- the geometrical ratio for consecutive edge length for U and V
- the polynomial degree for U and V
- the interpolation point number for U and V (>degree>=1)

ATTENTION: To obtain that the spline pass by the interpolation points
it is NECESSARY to choose
edge number = k ( interpolation point number - 1 ) (for U and for V)
The surface pass by the interpolation points but not necessary the
mesh which is an approximation of the spline surface!
Example: ROOF_CAR;  I; 3;
         defvar nax1,nay1; nax1=6; nay1=9; {variables utilisateur}
         nax1 {U VERTICES}; nay1 {V VERTICES};
         1    {U RATIO };   1;   {V RATIO }
         2    {U DEGREE};   3;   {V DEGREE}
         3    {U POINTS};   4;   {V POINTS}
         C3.1; C2.1; C1.1;  C3.2; C2.2; C1.2;
         C3.3; C2.3; C1.3;  C3.4; C2.4; C1.4; 
         {the interpolation points}

4 : SPLINE QUADRANGLE BY INTERPOLATION of LINES
The UNIFORM POLYNOMIAL SPLINE SURFACE is defined from
- the U edges number and its V edges number
  (In fact,U and V are the 2 parameters of the spline surface)
- the geometrical ratio for consecutive edge length for U and V
- the polynomial degree for U and V
- the number in V of interpolation lines(U)
- the name of interpolation lines(U)

6 : TRANSFINITE TRIANGLE
The triangle is defined by the 3 line edges.
The number of line edges (>0) may be the same for the 3 edges or not.
If the 3 numbers are equals a STRUCTURED triangulation is done.
Else an unstructured triangulation is created.

ATTENTION: The Maximum of edge length must be less than the sum
of the 2 other edges.

ATTENTION: With large oscillations on the edges, some triangles
may overlap! Draw the mesh to see if it is correct!
Example:   S6; I; 6; EDGE1; EDGE2; EDGE3;
La triangulation de la surface S9 respecte les sommets et aretes
du contour forme des 3 lignes EDGE1 EDGE2 EDGE3, l'ensemble devant
constituer une ligne fermee, pas trop distante d'un triangle.

8: QUADRANGULATION of a SQUARE or a CIRCLE
A central square or circle (or kernel) is regularly subdivided
Around homothetic layers beyond the kernel are constructed.
the DATA are:
-the NUMBER of EDGES in a direction of KERNEL
-the NUMBER of HOMOTHETIC LAYERS beyond KERNEL
-the LENGTH of square or circle KERNEL
-the TOTAL LENGTH of the square or circle

9 : TRIANGULATION BETWEEN CLOSED LINES
The DELAUNAY triangulation of a contour of closed lines
is obtained from a recovering of the domain by a quad-tree
of REGULAR TRIANGLES.

The number NBLFTR of CLOSED LINES of the BOUNDARY must be >=1.
The first line must be this one which contains all others.
Example:                 L1            (said ENVELOPE)
          ------------------------------------------------------
         |                                                      |
         |                                 /\                   | 
         |    ---------                   /  \ L3               | 
         |   |         |                 /    \                 |   
         |   |         |L2               \    /                 |
         |   |         |                  \  /                  | 
         |    ---------                    \/                   | 
         |                                                      |  
          ------------------------------------------------------  
Here, NBLFTR=3 LINES L1; L2; L3; to give with L1 ahead because
L1 "contains" L2 and L3.
The"HOLES" are given after the "ENVELOPE".

ARETMX is the length of a regular triangles which covers
completely the object.
Regular triangles with an edge length ARETMX will be created.

If the User has NOT given the 
DefFunc Taille_Ideale(x,y,z); ...  (as wished length!...)
then
  the triangles with a too great surface will be
  reduced by the introduction of their barycentre.
else
  The triangles will be made with edge lengths which
  verify Taille_Ideale(x,y,z)

This is the way to indicate around the point (x,y,z) what
the length of edges has to be!

Example for the input of Taille_Ideale:
DefVar lxf,lh2,lh3;
lh2=0.3;
lh3=0.7;
lxf=max(lh2,lh3);

DefFunc Taille_Ideale(x,y,z);
  Taille_Ideale=0.45;
  If x<lxf and y>-(lh3+lh2)*1.2
    Then Taille_Ideale=0.15;
  Else
    If x<lxf and y>-(lh3+lh2)*1.8
    Then Taille_Ideale=0.28;
    EndIf;
  EndIf;
EndFunc;

INTERNAL POINTS may be imposed as vertices of the triangulation
with a distance imposed to the neighboring vertices.

Example: CIRCLE; I; 9;
1.5; 2; 1; CIRCLE_LINE; HOLE; INTERNAL_PT; 0.01;
Define a triangulation of the domain interior limited by
the closed lines CIRCLE_LINE and HOLE;
with an edge length 1.5 of regular triangles and
an internal point INTERNAL_PT around of which the edges
of triangles must have a length < 0.01

10: INPUT DATA OF XYZSOMMET & NSEF TMS
These 2 arrays must be initialized, value by value
Example: REGULAR_TRIANGLE; I; 10;
         3;0;3; 0;0;0; 1;0;0;  0.5;sqrt(3)/2;0; {3 vertices Otg}
         3; 0; 4; 0; {surface notclosed 4vertices/FE 0tg}
         1; 0; 0; 0; {1triangle 0tg unstructured}
         1; 2; 3; 0; {4 numbers of the vertices}
define a regular triangle as a meshed surface.

11: 2D STRUCTURED RECTANGLE OF EDGES 1
La QUADRANGULATION du RECTANGLE [0,NBINQX] * [0,NBINQY] est
formee de carres de cotes de longueur 1.
Example: RECTANGLE11; I; 11; 7; 4;
Definit 7*4=28 carres de longueur 1, avec 7 ARETES en X et 4 en Y
Toute TRANSFORMATION est ensuite utilisable sur ce rectangle.

12: 2D STRUCTURED RECTANGULAR TRIANGLE
La TRIANGULATION du TRIANGLE (0,0) (NBINTR,0) (0,NBINTR) est
formee de TRIANGLES RECTANGLES UNITES.
Example: TRIANGLE12; I ; 12; 6;
Definit 6*6=36 triangles rectangles unites  
Toute TRANSFORMATION est ensuite utilisable sur ce triangle.

13: QUADRANGULATION OF A CONVEX CLOSED CURVE
with an EVEN NUMBER of EDGES
Quadrangulation d'une ligne convexe fermee avec un
nombre PAIR d'aretes. 2 aretes consecutives de la ligne sont
jointes au barycentre des sommets pour former un quadrangle.
Au total, le nombre de quadrangles est egal a la moitie du nombre
des aretes de la ligne convexe fermee.

14: SLICES FROM A GENERIC LINE or EXTRUSION
The GENERATRIC LINE is DISPLACED N times to create N slices.
The M generic line edges define NxM quadrangles
ATTENTION: these QUADRANGLES must NOT degenerate into
TRIANGLES or EDGES or POINTS.
The last displaced line may be the first line to form a crown.

The DISPLACEMENT of the GENERIC LINE may be defined by 7 options:

0: 3 points for each slice define the displacements
From the generic line is associated an orthonormal reference
system E0 defined by 3 points P01 P02 P03
.P01 is the origin
.P01-P02 define the first  vector E1
.P01-P03 define the second vector E2, thus
 E3 = E1 PRODUIT VECTORIEL E2
 E2 = E3 PRODUIT VECTORIEL E1
Norm(E1)=Norm(E2)=Norm(E3)=1
Each displacement I is defined by 3 points which define
a reference system EI as above.
The DISPLACEMENT of the GENERIC LINE is the MAPPING from E0 to Ei
The vertices from 2 consecutive lines are joined to define quadrangles
Example: S14.0; I; 14; GENERIC_LINE; 0; 2; {slide number}
         P01;P02;P03;  P11;P12;P13;   P21;P22;P23;
         {the 3 definition points of reference systems}

1: 3 line vertices define the mappings of the line
The reference sytems EI are defined as above with the I vertices
of the 3 lines.
E0 is defined by the first vertex of line 1 2 3
Ei is defined by the i-th  vertex of line 1 2 3 ...
Example: S14.1; I; 14; GENERIC_LINE; 1; L1; L2; L3;
        {the 3 lines of vertices definig the reference systems
         and the displacements of the generic line}

2: translation of a constant cote z>0 (a stack)
The generic line is translated of a constant cote Z>0 (stack)
Example: S14.2; I; 14; GENERIC_LINE; 2; 3; {slices}
         6; {cote maximum to cut into 3 slices of thickness Z=2}

3: translation of a cote z>0 for each displacement
The generic line is translated of a variable cote z>0 input
for each displacement
ATTENTION: This is an ABSOLUTE cote Z, NOT a RELATIVE cote
to the previous displacement
Example: S14.3; I; 14; GENERIC_LINE; 3; 2; {slices}
         4; 7; {absolute cote Z displacement of 2 slices}

4: translation vector (x y z) valuable for all slices
The previous line is translated of a CONSTANT VECTOR (NOT NULL!)
Example: S14.4; I; 14; GENERIC_LINE; 4; 5; {slices}
         1; 2; 3; {the 3 constant components of translation vector}

5: translation vectors (x y z) defined one by slice
The previous line is translated of a NON CONSTANT VECTOR,
ONE by slice.
Example: S14.5; I; 14; GENERIC_LINE; 5; 2; {slices}
1; 2; 3; {first translation of the generic line}
1; 2; 5; {translation of the previous line.  Translations add}

6: 3 functions X Y Z(no_slice,x,y,z) displace the generic line
The vertices of the generic line are mapped by these 3 functions
from R3 to R3.
For example: ABSCISSE(no_slice,x,y,z)
             ORDINATE(no_slice,x,y,z)
             COTE    (no_slice,x,y,z)
Each vertex (x,y,z) of the generic line becomes the vertex of coordinates
(ABSCISSE(no_slice,x,y,z), ORDINATE(no_slice,x,y,z),
 COTE    (no_slice,x,y,z) )  of the no_slice-th line
Example: 
DefFunc ABSCISSE(no_slice,x,y,z); ABSCISSE=no_slice*x; EndFunc;
DefFunc ORDINATE(no_slice,x,y,z); ORDINATE=no_slice*y; EndFunc;
DefFunc COTE(    no_slice,x,y,z); COTE    =no_slice*z; EndFunc;
S14.6; I; 14; GENERIC_LINE; 6; 5; {slices}
ABSCISSE; ORDINATE; COTE; {the 3 function names}

15: ROTATION OF A LINE AROUND AN AXIS
The generic line is rotated N times to create N slices.
The M edges of the generic line create N*M quadrangles.
Vertices may be on the rotation axis.
Then, the quadrangles become triangles. 
The total rotation angle<=360 degrees.
Examples: 
S15.0; I; 15; GENERIC_LINE; P1_AXE; P2_AXE; 36; {rotations}
0; {constant angles} 10; {degrees} 
Define a surface by 36 cumulated rotations of 10 degrees 
of GENERIC_LINE edges.                           

S15.1; I; 15; GENERIC_LINE; P1_AXE; P2_AXE; 4; {rotations}
1; {one angles by rotation}
20; 30; 40; 50; {degrees}
{rotations add from the generic line}
Define a surface by 4 rotations of 20 then 50 then 90
then 140 degrees of the GENERIC_LINE around the axis
defined by the points P1_AXE and P2_AXE

16: MAGNIFYING or EXTRUSING A LINE INTO LAYERS
The initial line must have all edges in the same sens.
In the normal direction to edges, a quadrangulation of NBCOLI(>0)
layers is done around.
All of layers have a small thickness EPCOLI to represent boundary layers
Then, NBDECO other layers are quadrangulated with a thickness which varies
linearly from EPCOLI to EPDECO.
Attention: If the normals cross each others, the quadrangulation may be
INCORRECT!... and the quadrangulation must be restricted in a vicinity
of the line.
If one of the thicknesses is negative, the 2 thicknesses are imposed
negative and the layers are made on the other side of the initial line.

17: 1/8 OF THE SURFACE OF A SPHERE
The regular triangulation is obtained by a regular subdivision
of the triangle 
of vertex 1 Centre + Rayon * (1,0,0)
of vertex 2 Centre + Rayon * (0,1,0)
of vertex 3 Centre + Rayon * (0,0,1) 
and projection of vertices on the sphere
Example: DEFVAR NT; NT=6; SPHERE_8; I; 17; NT**2; 1; CENTRE;
Define 36 triangles of vertices on the sphere/8 centred
at point CENTRE and of radius 1 situe in the sector X Y Z >0

18: 1/1 OF THE SURFACE OF A SPHERE
The regular triangulation is the regular subdivision
of 20 regular triangles of an icosahedron with its
12 vertices on the sphere and the projection of added
vertices on the sphere.
Example: DEFVAR N; N=5; SPHERE18; I; 18; 20*N**2; 1; CENTRE;
Define 500 triangles of vertices on the sphere centred
at point CENTRE and of radius 1. 
ATTENTION: The triangles, excepted case N=1,
are not exactly regular
 
19: TRIANGULATION2  OF CLOSED LINES BY SUBDIVISION
Data are same as option 9: TRIANGULATION1.
Only the triangulation algorithm changes.
It creates triangles from the edges of the closed lines of the
boundary. After, it adds the internal points of a regular grid
from the data of the value ARETMX of the edge length or
the function EDGE_LENGTH(x,y,z). Then, the triangulation quality
is augmented.

20: EXTRUDED SURFACES of a PLANE POLYGON
An opened or closed polygon is translated of the vector defined
by 2 points. If the polygon is closed, the final surface is closed
and defined the boundary of a solid.
2 possibilities to indicate the length of edges:
. Option 0 of debut menu: the constant length is used
. Option the function EDGE_LENGTH(x,y,z) at the point x,y,z

21: CLOSED SURFACE of a BOX or RECTANGULAR PARALLELIPIPEDRON
From a CENTRE point , a X LENGTH, a Y WIDTH, a Z HEIGHT,
the surface of a RECTANGULAR PARALLELIPIPEDRON, i.e. its
6 rectangular faces, is triangulated from the data
. Option 0 of debut menu: the constant edge length is used
. Option the function EDGE_LENGTH(x,y,z) at the point x,y,z

22: CLOSED SURFACE of a CYLINDER or a CONE
The axis is defined by 2 points, inferior and superior.
In the perpendicular plan to the axis, the radii, inferior and
superior define the 2 circles. With 2 different radii, the cylinder
becomes a trunc of a CONE. The edge length is defined by
. Option 0 of debut menu: the constant length is used
. Option the function EDGE_LENGTH(x,y,z) at the point x,y,z

23: CLOSED SURFACE of a TORUS
The torus centre point, a X axis point, a Y axis point,
the GREAT and SMALL radius define the TORUS.
The constant length (option 0 of debut menu) gives a
quadrangulation of the torus.
The edge length defined by the function EDGE_LENGTH(x,y,z)
at the point x,y,z creates a triangulation on the tore.

27: ANGULAR SECTOR OF A CYLINDER
The surface is that of a quadrangle on a cylinder
in the plane Z=0 an arc of circle and 
in the plane Z>0 an other arc of circle (=> truncated cone)
The degree constant angle is measured from the X-axis.
The cylinder axis is defined from the origin of reference system
and a point (to define also the superior plane).
The edge length in the height or in the sector angular may be
computed with a geometrical ratio or not.
Example: S21; i; 21;
18; {edges for the angle}
1;  {constant length}
2; 3; {circle radius in planes Z=O and superior}
180;  {degrees for 1/2 cylindre (360 is available)}
5;{height edges} 1.2; {geometrical ratio for angles}
CENTRE_CIRCLE_SUP; {Define axis ORIGIN-this POINT}
Define an half cylinder, of axis  ORIGINE-CENTRE_CIRCLE_SUP,
with a mesh of 18*5=90 quadrangles.

