29: MODIFY a 2D or 3D MESH WITH MENUS AND MOUSE
From a mesh of triangles and/or quadrangles (divided into 2 triangles)
it is possible with the mouse and its buttons to define point or vertex
or triangle and modify the mesh with the options:

 1: 'DISPLACE(Button1) or ORBIT(button2) or ZOOM(Button3) the MESH'
     Exit by Escape

  2: 'MOVE a VERTEX'
     2 clicks: First to define the vertex, Second to define the new position

  3: 'BACK to the INITIAL XYZ of the VERTEX'
      Return to the initial XYZ of the last moved vertex

  4: 'DELETE a VERTEX'
      If internal vertex, triangulation of the triangles with this vertex
      If external vertex, suppression of the triangles with this vertex

  5: 'ADD a VERTEX INSIDE a TRIANGLE'
      1 click inside a triangle => 3 sub-triangles into this triangle

  6: 'CUT a COMMON EDGE of 2 TRIANGLES'
      1 click defines the edge. Creation of a vertex, middle of the edge.
      A triangle gives 2 sub-triangles.

  7: 'EXCHANGE a DIAGONAL of 2 TRIANGLES'
      1 click inside a triangle => Swap the diagonals

  8: 'DELAUNAY TRIANGULATION'
      From a common edge to 2 triangles, Swap the diagonals if
      R1+R2 > R3+R4 where R is the circomcribed circle radius of a triangle
      for the 2 choices of 2 triangles

  9: '3 VERTICES CREATE 1 TRIANGLE'
      3 clicks to define the 3 vertices of the new triangle

 10: '1 EXTERNAL POINT+2 VERTICES CREATE 1 TRIANGLE'
      in 2D: 1 click define a new vertex outside the mesh
      in 3D: Type the X Y Z of the new vertex, outside the mesh
      2 clicks to define the 2 other vertices of the new triangle

 11: 'DELETE a 3D TRIANGLE'
      1 click inside a triangle and the triangle is deleted

 90: 'STOP and SAVE the MODIFICATIONS'


30: QUALITY IMPROVEMENT OF A TRIANGULATION
For a TRIANGLE the QUALITY = c * r /R where
r is the inscribed     radius circle of the triangle
R is the circumscribed radius circle of the triangle
c is a coefficient to have 1 for the regular triangle.
Its value is between 0 (degenerated FE) and 1 (regular FE).

The triangles of bad quality may be suppressed
- either by swapping of diagonals of quadrangle formed by 2 triangles
with a common edge
- or if its smaller angle is very small
- or by subdivision into 2 triangles with the adjacent triangle
  by the greatest edge opposed to the greatest angle (>160 degres)
If triangle quality<QUALMN then, it is deleted
If QUALMN=0, only the swapping of diagonals is tried.
The adjacent triangulation is improved if the angle between
their 2 planes <= ANGL2P.
Example: S30_IMPROVED_TRIANGULATION; I; 30; TRIANGULATION;
         0.1; {QUALMN}  6; {degrees for ANGL2P}  
ATTENTION: The geometrie is approached and not strictly respected.


31: TRIANGULATION OF A QUADRANGULATION
Each of quadrangles    S4------S3
                       |       |
                       S1------S2
of the surface mesh are cut into 2 triangles as the options:
1: S1-S2-S3  and  S1-S3-S4
2: S1-S2-S4  and  S2-S3-S4
3: the geatest angle is cut
Example: S31_TRIANGULATION; I; 31; QUADRANGULATION; 3; 

32: JUNCTION 1 POINT TO EDGES OF A LINE
the triangle vertices are the point and the 2 vertices of
each edge of the line. This option permits to close surfaces
by a cone or a trucated cone.
Example: S32; I; 32; CENTRE; LINE_TO_JOIN;

33: JONCTION BETWEEN EDGES OF LINES
Attention:
- The lines are supposed almost parallel, and do NOT cut
  each others
- The edge number between 2 successive lines may be equal
(creation of quadrangles) or be different of 1
(creation of triangles).
Example: S33; I; 33;  5; {lines}
L1;L2;L3;L4;L5; {names of lines}

34: STRUCTURED QUADRANGLE FROM A STRUCTURED HEXAHEDRON
2 intervals of vertex numbers among the 3 intervals of variation 
of vertex indexes of a STRUCTURED HEXAHEDRON are given to define
the extracted quadrangle.
One of the 3 required intervals must be reduced to one value
For a direction (I or J or K), the minimum vertex number is 1
and the maximum vertex number is the edge number + 1.
Example: S34; I; 34; STRUCTURED_VOLUME;
         2;5; 4;8;  1;1; {extracted intervals}
Extract the quadrangle S34 with the vertices 2 to 5 of I-index,
the vertices 4 to 8 of J-index and K-index=1.

35: STRUCTURED QUADRANGLE FROM A STRUCTURED QUADRANGLE
Extrct a quadrangulation defined by 2 intervalles of edge number
among the 2 edge indexes of the structured quadrangle
Example: S35; I; 35; STRUCTURED_QUADRANGLE; 2;5; 4;5;
Extract the quadrangle of 3 slices 2 to 5 in the I-direction of edges
and  4 to 5 in the J-direction of edges.
                                  
36: EXTRACTED SURFACE FROM A SURFACE from a criterion FUNCTION
Any triangle or quadrangle with all their vertices giving true
for the logical User's function belongs to the extracted surface
Example: S36; I; 36; INITIAL_SURFACE;
deffunc PLANE_X_POSITIF(x,y,z); 
  PLANE_X_POSITIF = (x>=-0.00001);
endfunc;
PLANE_X_POSITIF;
extract the triangles and/or quadrangles with all vertices
which have an abscisse >= -0.00001 (for troncature errors)
                                      
37: EXTRACTED SURFACE FROM FACES OF A VOLUME
Any triangle or quadrangle, FE face of the volume mesh
with all their vertices giving true
for the logical User's function belongs to the extracted surface
Example: S37; I; 37; VOLUME;
deffunc Z_POSITIF(x,y,z);
        Z_POSITIF = z>0.00001; finfonc;
        Z_POSITIF;
        3; {type of extracted FE faces}
extract the triangles or quadrangles with all vertices of Z>0 
faces dont les sommets ont une cote >0
The TYPE of EXTRACTED FE faces may be
1 : ONLY boundary faces (belongs to one and only one FE)
2 : ONLY internal faces (belongs to 2 and only 2 FE)
3 : boundary and internal faces

38: EXTRACT SURFACE BY CLICKING FROM A SURFACE
The triangles or quadrangles, such that all vertices are inside a
rectangle defined by 2 clicks, are extracted
In 3D, the using of the normal vector, avoid to obtain the not
visible triangles.

39: SUBDIVISION INTO 4 SUB FINITE ELEMENTS of EVERY 2D FINITE ELEMENT

40: EXTRACT SURFACE = SURFACE1 - SURFACE2
The FE of surface2 are suppressed of the FE of surface1.
Attention, the FE of surface2 must belong of surface1

41: EXTRACT 3D SURFACE if (NORMAL,VECTOR)>=0
Extract a triangle or quadrangle of a surface if the dot
product (NORMAL,VECTOR)>=0 at all its vertices.

42: G1-CONTINUITY OF SURFACES WITH TANGENTS
At each vertex with tangents to the adjacent edges, a plane is
defined to pass trough this vertex and minimize the square of
distances of the extremities of tangents.
Thus, these extremities are projected to this plane.
Thus, the surface mesh at this vertex becomes G1-CONTINUOUS.
Example: S42; i; 42; abcde;
The surface S42 has at each vertex all its tangents in a same plane

45: LOGICAL OPERATORS ON 2 2D-SURFACE MESHES or 3D-SURFACE MESHES
In R3, the 2 SURFACES must be CLOSED, i.e. , every edge belongs to
2 triangles, boundary of 2 solids.
From 2 meshed surfaces S1 and S2 of plane XoY or R3, it is
possible to construct a triangulation of the surfaces
S1 intersection S2, or S1 + S2, or S1 - S2.
The resulting mesh is a triangulation.
  
48: IMPOSED POINTS ONTO the NEAREST VERTEX of the SURFACE
    The 3 coordinates of the nearest vertex to a named point
    are replaced by the 3 coordinates of the point.
    Attention, the quality of finite elements may be modified.

50: MAPPING OF A SURFACE
An existing surface is transformed by a predefined MAPPING
Example: S50; PLANE_SYMMETRY; 50; INITIAL_SURFACE;
The vertices of the SURFACE S50 are the images of vertices
of INITIAL_SURFACE by the mapping PLANE_SYMMETRY

51: C0-CONTINUITY UNION OF SURFACES
The resulting surface will be an UNION of surfaces grouped
under a same name.
An UNION of surfaces is handled after as any other surface
The common vertices of 2 surfaces are identified
to form an unique vertex. If this identification is NOT
correct, modify the identification precision EPZERO and EPSXYZ
of vertices by the option 20 of the Debut menu.
Example: S51; I; 51; 5; S1;S2;S3;S4;S5;

52: G1-CONTINUITY UNION OF SURFACES
At each vertex of the surface union, with tangents to the adjacent
edges, a plane is defined to pass trough this vertex and minimize
the square of distances of the extremities of tangents.
Thus, these extremities are projected to this plane.
Thus, the union surface mesh at this vertex becomes G1-CONTINUOUS.
Example: S52; i; 52; 2; abe; bcde;
The surface S52, union of surfaces abe and bcde, has at each of its
vertices all its tangents in a same plane.

